```java
import java.util.HashMap;

public class LongestSubstringWithoutRepeatingChars {
    public static int lengthOfLongestSubstring(String s) {
        if (s == null || s.length() == 0) {
            return 0;
        }

        int maxLength = 0;
        int start = 0;
        HashMap<Character, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        for (int end = 0; end < s.length(); end++) {
            char c = s.charAt(end);
            if (map.containsKey(c)) {
                start = Math.max(start, map.get(c) + 1);
            }
            map.put(c, end);
            maxLength = Math.max(maxLength, end - start + 1);
        }

        return maxLength;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String s = "abcabcbb";
        System.out.println("Length of the longest substring without repeating characters: " + lengthOfLongestSubstring(s));
    }
}
```

This code defines a method `lengthOfLongestSubstring` that takes a string `s` as input and returns the length of the longest substring without repeating characters. The main logic uses a sliding window approach with a HashMap to keep track of the last index of each character. The `start` pointer is updated whenever a repeating character is found, and the maximum length is continuously updated.

